value.value: A finding of both erosion and ulceration in the same lesion.
The formation of fibrous tissue characterized by an increased number of active, plump fibroblasts and variable amounts of collagen.
A group of cell that show altered characteristics in comparison to normal cell types and are confined to a specific area of the sample.
Confirmatory presence of fungal microorganisms.
Disturbance of cellular integrity and deterioration of germ cells.
Reduction in the number of germ cells.

label.value: Germ Cell Depletion and Germ Cell Degeneration

value.value: A finding of both germ cell depletion and germ cell degeneration.
Chronic degenerative changes in the glomeruli characterized by loss of cellularity of glomerular capillary tufts and acellular deposition of immunoglobulins.
A hardening of the kidney glomerulus caused by scarring of the blood vessels.
A congenital abnormality found in Fisher 344 rats characterized by grossly visible nodule(s) usually located on the median lobe of the liver.
A finding of both hyperplastic and metaplastic changes in a pathologic process.
A finding of both hypertrophy and hyperplasia in the same lesion.
A finding of both hypertrophy and karyomegaly in the same lesion.
Incomplete or underdevelopment of a tissue or organ.
An increase in nuclear size and amount of cytoplasm of a cell. The cells or nucleus may be slightly irregular and/or may be polyploid.
A finding of both karyocytomegaly and multinucleated hepatocytes in the same lesion.
An increase in the size of a cellular nucleus.
A process characterized by the degeneration of mesangial cells and the dissolution of the mesangial matrix in the glomerulus of the kidney, in response to injury or disease.
An accumulation of microglial cells in nervous tissue as a result of injury.
The process by which an organic substance is converted into organic minerals, such as in the formation of bone.
A parent class of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons containing four fused rings. (IUPAC 1998)
A giant hepatocyte with multiple nuclei.
The phagocytic destruction of nerve cells.
Renal damage and impaired renal function secondary to urinary tract obstruction.
Confirmatory presence of parasitic microorganisms.

A loosely organized mass found in the bladder and/or urethra of male rats, composed of eosinophilic material intermingled with exfoliated urothelial cells, and occasionally containing spermatozoa. Plug formation is assumed to be a result of abnormal ejaculation and secretions from the male accessory sex glands, and may occur during euthanasia.
Chronic kidney damage due to vesicoureteral reflux.
An alteration of the septum from the midline.
Stoppage of flow of sperm due to obstruction.
Persistence of mature elongating spermatids in the seminiferous tubules after the normal stage of physiologic release.
A benign cystic dilatation in the head of the epididymis that contains milky or watery fluid and spermatozoa.
A focus of hepatocytes containing well delineated circular clear spaces in the liver, often near mesenteric attachments such as the falciform ligament.

An abnormal and pathological astrocyte which appears enlarged and metabolically hyperactive. It is characterized by the presence of vesicular and basophilic nuclei. This cell type is not associated with Alzheimer's Disease.
An abnormal fluid-filled cleft (e.g. as in the epidermis) or membrane-bound space.
Confirmatory presence of yeast microorganisms.
A measurement of a subject's physical activity or movement.
The average rate of pressure change over time within the left ventricle, which is used as a measurement of left ventricular contractility.
The maximum rate of positive pressure (systolic) change within the left ventricle during a unit time.
The minimum rate of positive pressure (systolic) change within the left ventricle during a unit time.
The maximum rate of negative pressure (diastolic) change within the left ventricle during a unit time.
The pressure within the left ventricle following the completion of diastolic filling, just prior to systole.
The pressure in the left ventricle at any point prior to the ejection of its contents into the aorta (systole).
The maximum time between the recording of a Q wave on ECG and the onset of the aortic blood pressure pulse.

The calculated average time period between the recording of a Q wave on ECG and the onset of the aortic blood pressure pulse as determined over a number of cardiac cycles during a given interval of time.
The median time period between the recording of a Q wave on ECG and the onset of the aortic blood pressure pulse as determined over a number of cardiac cycles during a given interval of time.
The minimum time between the recording of a Q wave on ECG and the onset of the aortic blood pressure pulse.
